{"cursor":"19262","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"In mathematics, more specifically ring theory, a branch of abstract algebra, the\n'Jacobson radical' of a ring R is an ideal which consists of those elements in R\nwhich annihilate all simple right R-modules. It happens that substituting \"left\"\nin place of \"right\" in the definition yields the same ideal, and so the notion\nis left-right symmetric. The Jacobson radical of a ring is frequently denoted by\nJ(R) or rad(R); however to avoid confusion with other radicals of rings, the\nformer notation will be preferred in this article. The Jacobson radical is named\nafter Nathan Jacobson, who was the first to study it for arbitrary rings in .\n\nThe Jacobson radical of a ring has numerous internal characterizations,\nincluding a few definitions which successfully extend the notion to rings\nwithout unity. The radical of a module extends the definition of the Jacobson\nradical to include modules. The Jacobson radical plays a prominent role in many\nring and module theoretic results, such as Nakayama's lemma.   ","linknr":228,"url":"Jacobson_radical","recorded":1362896636,"links":19,"instances":["mathematics","mathematics","ring_theory","algebra","algebra","ring_theory","mathematics","mathematics"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Ideals","Ring theory"],"headings":["Intuitive discussion","Equivalent characterizations","Examples","Properties","Notes","References","See also"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/math/4/f/c/4fcf0dcff2eb0e044cb65afaeb64f97e.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/0/d/6/0d6aee1ab13bf4a94644ef82ee31762c.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/6/d/2/6d28f02961990fcc13acc6feafe6347a.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/5/5/355e6161f58b626b211515dc92382bd6.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/0/9/0/090ae1c1b574312a3721550ecb3d25bf.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/7/4/c/74c729719b8f0a72af49c0a9ca522239.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.